//- Use the presentation layout so we can keep this clean
extends layouts/presentation

block append config
  -
    config.theme = 'lengstorf';
    config.title = 'Breaking In';
    config.description = 'How to Land Your Dream Job in Tech';

    config.author = {
      name: 'Jason Lengstorf',
      email: 'jason@gatsbyjs.com',
      link: 'https://lengstorf.com/',
      twitter: 'jlengstorf',
      github: 'jlengstorf',
    };
    
    config.slides = {
      link: 'https://git.io/get-a-tech-job',
    };

    config.conference = {
      hashtag: 'pdxFLiT',
      twitter: 'pdxFLiT',
    };
  -

//- Add your slides here. See templates/includes/_mixins.pug for information 
//- on how `+slide` works.
block slides
  +slide
    h1(style="font-size: 110px; margin-bottom: 0")= config.title
    h4= config.description
    
    p by 
      a(href= config.author.link)= config.author.name
      br
      small
        a(href= `https://twitter.com/${config.author.twitter}`)= `@${config.author.twitter}`
        | &nbsp; ¬∑ &nbsp;
        a(href= `mailto:${config.author.email}`)= config.author.email
    
    p
      small Slides: #[a(href= config.slides.link)= config.slides.link.replace('https://', '')]

  +slide
    blockquote.photo-quote
      .photo
        img(
          src="./images/jason-lengstorf.jpg"
          alt="Jason Lengstorf"
        )
      .quote
        ul(style="list-style: none;")
          li Human Duct Tape @ Gatsby
          li Formerly: IBM
          li Portland, OR
  
  +slide
    h2 Hiring in tech is 
      span.underlined(style="font-size: 216%") broken
  
  +slide
    h3 We #[em should] hire based on:
    ul
      li.fragment Potential for learning and growth
      li.fragment Compatible core values
      li.fragment Demonstrated ability to do the job
      li.fragment Core personality traits (e.g. grit)

  +slide
    h3 Instead, we hire based on the #[strong wrong] signals:
    ul
      li.fragment Ability to answer computer science trivia questions
      li.fragment Whether or not we‚Äôve heard of you
      li.fragment Which of our friends referred you

  +slide
    h2.no-margin This is 
      strong no good
    h4.no-margin.fragment ...but don‚Äôt lose hope just yet

  +slide
    h4 If you know #[span.underlined how] the system is broken
    h4.no-margin.fragment you can leverage it to land your 
      em dream job

  +slide
    h3 3 steps to land your dream job in tech
    ol
      li.fragment Show up.
      li.fragment Show love.
      li.fragment Share.

  +slide
    h1.no-margin 1. Show up
    blockquote.no-margin
      p.
        You keep showing up, and you keep showing up, and, eventually, 
        somebody notices.
      p.no-margin
        small ‚Äì Joey Diaz

  +slide
    h2 Do something small 
      span.underlined every day
    ul
      li.fragment Learn one thing every day and share it on Twitter. 
      li.fragment Reach out to one person in the tech community. 
      li.fragment Write for 10 minutes about what you learned the day before and publish on your blog. 
   
  +slide
    figure
      img(
        src="images/get-a-tech-job/marginal-gains-graph.jpg"
        alt="Comparison of 1% better and 1% worse every day."
        style="max-width: 600px"
      )
      figcaption Image credit: 
        a(href="https://jamesclear.com/marginal-gains") James Clear
    aside.notes.
      Taken in isolation, any one small action won‚Äôt feel like much. But
      in aggregate, one small action every day makes an enormous difference
      over time.

  +slide
    h3 How this helps you:
    ul
      li.fragment Creates a body of public work
      li.fragment Helps you show up in discussions & on newsfeeds
      li.fragment Grows your network
      li.fragment Starts real conversations with industry peers
  
  +slide
    h2 Don‚Äôt forget about 
      span(style="font-size: 134%") cognitive bias:
    p The #[a(href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mere-exposure_effect") mere-exposure effect] means you‚Äôre more likely to get a chance if people have heard of you before.
  

  +slide
    h3.no-margin Doing it right:
    figure.no-margin
      img(
        src="images/get-a-tech-job/katieofcode.png"
        alt="Katie Fujihara‚Äôs Twitter profile."
        style="max-width: 600px"
      )
      figcaption
        a(href="https://twitter.com/katieofcode") Katie Fujihara on Twitter
    aside.notes.
      Katie has consistently put the work into local events, meeting local 
      and online peers, and growing her network. She‚Äôs slowly, methodically 
      created a public body of work, made contacts in the industry, and ‚Äî 
      recently ‚Äî landed her first job!

  +slide
    h1.no-margin 2. Show love
    blockquote.no-margin
      p Work hard, be kind, and amazing things will happen.
      p.no-margin
        small ‚Äì Conan O'Brien

  +slide
    h3 Kindness is a career 
      span(style="font-size:142%").underlined supercharger
    ul
      li.fragment Be helpful whenever you have the chance.
      li.fragment Never cut people down or talk trash.
      li.fragment Assume the best intentions and treat people accordingly.

  +slide
    h4 When you‚Äôre unkind, we notice
    blockquote.twitter-tweet(data-conversation="none")
      p(lang="en" dir="ltr") It‚Äôs easy to teach someone to code. It‚Äôs really hard to teach someone not to be an asshole.
      | &mdash; Jason Lengstorf (@jlengstorf)
      a(href="https://twitter.com/jlengstorf/status/1068968037523443712?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw") December 1, 2018
    aside.notes.
      I know a lot of extremely smart people that I would never hire or 
      recommend after seeing the way they treat other people on the internet.

  +slide
    h3 How this helps you:
    ul
      li.fragment The best teams place high value on team members who make the people around them better
      li.fragment The community notices and builds up kind people
      li.fragment In tech ‚Äî unfortunately ‚Äî ‚Äúnot being a dick‚Äù can be a differentiator üòî

  +slide
    h2 Don‚Äôt forget about 
      span(style="font-size: 134%") cognitive bias:
    p The #[a(href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reciprocity_(social_psychology)") reciprocity bias] means people are more likely to help you if you‚Äôve helped them before.


  +slide
    h1.no-margin 3. Share
    blockquote.no-margin
      p Generosity is the best investment.
      p.no-margin
        small ‚Äì Diane Con Furstenberg

  +slide
    h3 Work and learn in public whenever possible
    ul
      li.fragment Open source your personal sites and projects.
      li.fragment Take notes in a public place, like your blog or Medium.
      li.fragment Contribute to open source projects, even if it‚Äôs ‚Äújust‚Äù docs improvements.
    aside.notes.
      Correct or not, employers will give a lot of weight to an active 
      GitHub profile. By doing anything that can be done on GitHub on GitHub,
      it creates an image that employer‚Äôs value: an active developer, engaged
      in the community, working on popular open source projects, etc.
  
  +slide
    h3 If you want to get started, start here:
    figure
      img(
        src="images/get-a-tech-job/gatsby.png"
        alt="Gatsby‚Äôs first-time contributor message on GitHub."
      )

  +slide
    h2 Don‚Äôt forget about 
      span(style="font-size: 134%") cognitive bias:
    p The #[a(href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Halo_effect") halo effect] means people will judge you more favorably if you‚Äôre associated with things they value (like popular OSS projects).

  +slide
    h2 But what about coding interviews?
    p.fragment You can #[a(href="https://blog.usejournal.com/i-interviewed-at-six-top-companies-in-silicon-valley-in-six-days-and-stumbled-into-six-job-offers-fe9cc7bbc996") study for coding interviews] and ace them.

  +slide
    h2 Recap
    ul
      li.fragment The hiring process in tech is broken
      li.fragment If you learn #[em how] it‚Äôs broken, you can use it to your advantage
      li.fragment Frequently and consistently post work and learn in public to build your network and a body of work
      li.fragment Be kind and helpful to everyone ‚Äî¬†you never know who‚Äôs hiring
      li.fragment Don‚Äôt give up and don‚Äôt stop learning

  //- Thanks & Resources
  +slide
    h1.no-margin Thanks!
    img(
